notesStmt.note: Incipit: Saepenumero animadverti complures advenas prudentas homines, nec bonorum artium ignaros, qui cum primum Venetias venissent...

Explicit: Si enim quippiam bonum a Deo immortali hominibus provenire credibile ist, hoc praecipue divinitus Venetae urbi obtigisse persuasissimum cuilibet esse debet. Libri quinti et totius operis finis.
Moderate oxidation of ink, books 1-3, a few folios illegible.

msIdentifier.repository: Kislak Center for Special Collections, Rare Books and Manuscripts

msContents.summary: A work in five books on the history and government of Venice.

supportDesc.extent: 92 leaves : 201 x 142 (149 x 98) mm. bound to 209 x 142 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Paper, i (modern paper) + 92 + i (modern paper); [i], 1-90, [i]; contemporary foliation in ink, upper right recto.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in an italic script by a single hand, with contemporary or near contemporary marginal notes.

origin.p: Written in Italy in the mid-16th century (Zacour-Hirsch).

history.provenance: Formerly in the collection of the Morbio Library (Rosenthal).
Sold by Guillaume Libri at auction at Sotheby's, 28 March 1859, lot 282.
